communications.subject: North Carolina Public Records Law Request: Mark Mambula report
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the North Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

-OCSO incident report #2017006215 pertaining to the 15Apr17 death of V/MAMBULAO
-all publicly available investigative and police reports pertaining to the aforementioned death

I'm requesting these documents as part of a story for WIRED magazine about the opioid crisis.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Benoit Morenne

communications.subject: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Hedge Fund Request
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

You kindly sent us copies of your records that show information as listed below dated to June 30 2024. Please will it be possible to have an update on any records that would show some or all of the following information:
1. A list of ALL hedge funds and fund of hedge funds in which Richmond Retirement System is an investor; and
2. For each hedge fund and fund of hedge funds, may I please have a copy of any records that would show some or all of the following information:
a. the month by month market value of Richmond Retirement System's holding in each fund from July 1 2024 to September 30 2024
b. the month by month amount invested by Richmond Retirement System in each fund from July 1 2024 to September 30 2024
c. the month by month net returns (net of fees) earned by Richmond Retirement System on its investment in each fund from July 1 2024 to September 30 2024

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tom Nash, a citizen of Virginia, in coordination with Haley Parker.

Autopsy report for Carla Renee Chapel whose death occurred May 25 2015 in Grand Prairie, Tx.

Sincerely,

Tiffanie Chapel

communications.subject: Ohio Open Records Law Request: FOIA Request for Case-Related Materials
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Ohio Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am writing to formally request access to public records under the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA). Specifically, I am requesting any and all records and materials related to the case of

Suspect Name: Adam Coy
Description/Headline: https://eu.dispatch.com/story/news/courts/2024/10/18/columbus-police-officer-adam-coy-shooting-death-andre-hill-ohio/75500260007/
Link of the Article: Former Columbus police officer Adam Coy to face trial in 2020 shooting of Andre Hill
State: ohio 
Law Enforcement: ohio police 

included but not limited to the following:
Documents:
Incident reports
Investigation reports
Officer statements
Witness statements
Any other relevant case files

Footage:
Body camera footage from officers on the scene
Dash camera footage
Police surveillance camera footage
Private/public surveillance footage from nearby locations
Any footage collected as evidence or during the investigation

Audio:
911 calls
Police radio communications
Any other audio recordings related to the case

Visual Media:
Crime scene photographs
Surveillance stills
Photographs taken during the investigation

Court Records:
Transcripts from court hearings or proceedings
Any video/audio footage from court hearings
Court orders or any other court-related documents

Please include any and all materials, regardless of format (digital or physical), including those not listed above that are related to the case in question.
Additionally, if this request has been sent to the wrong department or agency, I would appreciate it if you could provide guidance or contact information for the correct department or agency that handles such requests.

If any part of the request is denied or redacted, please provide a detailed explanation of the specific legal exemption that applies.
Thank you for your attention to this matter. I look forward to your timely response within the period mandated by FOIA

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

david yupa

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Layla the Mighty Minter
communications.communication:
Dear U.S. Mint:

This is a request for records under the Freedom of Information Act. I am requesting records related to the U.S. Mint's mascot, Layla the Mighty Minter.

RECORDS REQUESTED:

(A) All records related to the conception of and process of designing the Layla mascot (emails and other correspondence, memoranda, contracts, sketches, etc.)

(B) Records sufficient to answer the following questions:

(1) Whose idea was it to create an U.S. Mint mascot in the first place, and why?

(2) Who designed the Layla mascot, and what was the design process like? (e.g. were there multiple design concepts submitted? Was the design of the character contracted out? (If so, kindly produce the contract).

(3) Were any Layla-related promotional items or tchotchkes created (e.g. trading cards, CDs, coloring books)? If so, please produce them.

(4) Were there any life-size Layla costumes created? If so, please produce records related to the design of the costume (contracts, sketches, etc.) and any guidelines regarding the use of or care for the costume.

(5) Did anyone in Congress ever object to the U.S. Mint's use of a mascot? I understand that there have been periodic attempts by lawmakers (e.g. former Oklahoma senator Tom Coburn, current Iowa senator Jodi Ernst) to rein in agency spending on mascots. If so, please produce all records related to that.

(6) What has the public's reaction been to the Layla mascot?

(7) Is the Mint still using Layla as part of its public outreach? If not, why not?

REQUEST FOR FEE WAIVER:

The requested documents will be made available to the general public online for free, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. I am working on a project examining the history, creation, evolution, and use of mascots across the federal government—because, like many others, I find them fascinating and weirdly delightful. Thus, I respectfully request that any fees related to this request be waived. If you do decide to charge me fees, please notify me in advance if you expect those fees to exceed $25.

FORM OF PRODUCTION:

I would prefer that this request be filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

CONCLUSION:

Thank you very much for your cooperation with this request. I look forward to hearing from you soon!

Sincerely,

Nicholas Marritz

communications.subject: Reaching out
communications.communication:
Off the record, please, not for publication:

Dear Mr. Marritz,

Not sure if this email will reach you, but wanted to contact you after seeing your name and email listed on a FOIA request regarding US Mint mascots.

I'm following up on Senator Ernst's previous work highlighting mascots at the US Mint, and wanted to thank you for doggedly (or should I say DOGE'edly) pursuing an answer from them!

We had not seen these documents before I came across them, and your work, today.

Would love to chat with you about your work, and any other FOIA's you've been involved in that might help us draw attention to wasteful government spending.

Thanks,
Sheila

Sheila Cole
Office of Senator Joni Ernst (R-IA)
Sheila_Cole@ernst.senate.gov





Mr. Nicholas Marritz
MuckRock News, DEPT MR134412, 263 Huntington
11 Dupont Circle, N.W., Suite 400
Boston, M.A. 02115
Email: 134412-98926929@requests.muckrock.com<mailto:134412-98926929@requests.muckrock.com>
FOIA Request 2022-MINT-00094

Dear Mr. Marritz:
This is in response to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request submitted via

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Chief FOIA officer's recent email (Selective Service System)
communications.communication:
Dear Selective Service System,

On behalf of myself and Fiat Fiendum, I hereby request the following records:

1. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's email inbox or equivalent which was received nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
2. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's email spam folder or equivalent which was received nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
3. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's sent email folder or equivalent which was sent nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
4. The total full-time equivalent count of people who work for your FOIA office as of October 19, 2024.

This request is expressly limited to Selective Service System's own FOIA office. Please do not refer it to any other agency or division. This request is expressly not a Privacy Act request, and no PA waiver will be provided.

Please provide the email records in EML, Maildir, MBOX, MIX, MSG, or PST format only — not PDF, Word, image, etc — including all metadata (e.g. full email headers as received/sent) and attachments, without alteration other than narrowly tailored electronic redaction of specifically claimed exemptions that do not affect any part of non exempt information (and, in particular, without rasterization).

Please provide the fourth record as a statement in your response letter, or at your option, as the most readily available record, in original electronic format as currently stored on your computer systems, which includes that information.

Please provide all records either as individual files, or as an unencrypted ZIP file, uploaded to MuckRock. Do not apply any encryption, DRM, or other restriction.

I request fee waiver, because
* Fiat Fiendum is a 501(c)(3) non-profit;
* this request is for public interest, non-commercial purposes;
* these records would give a snapshot of insight into the everyday processes of FOIA offices; and
* these records are being requested in order to conduct a government-wide audit of agencies' FOIA compliance.

In the event that you deny fee waiver, please process this request as-is, because I will not agree to any fees.

Please be sure to provide:
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(II) FOIA Public Liaison information
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(III)(aa) appeal information
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(III)(bb) OGIS information
* 5 USC 552(a)(7)(A) tracking number
* 5 USC 552(a)(7)(B)(ii) completion ETA

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,
Sai
President, Fiat Fiendum, Inc.

P.S. Sai is my full legal name.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request: Chief FOIA officer's recent email (Selective Service System)
communications.communication:
Dear SSS,

Thank you for your extremely quick response. I appeal your search and claim of no records, and your violation of my form and format request.

As for form and format, you stated that you were providing one email, and sent it as a PDF. You did not claim any exemptions.

By exporting it to PDF, you disregarded my electronic form & format requests — and you additionally rasterized the record, which I specifically asked you not to do. OCR does not cure the destruction of the original structural metadata that makes it accessible, nor make available the parts of the records (such as hyperlinks, headers, etc) which were destroyed by rasterization. I did not consent to you making new, worse records in this way.

Please provide the email in one of the native electronic email formats listed; any email software will save to them easily.

My form and format request is mandatory under 5 USC 552(a)(3)(B & C) & (f)(2)(A) (E-FOIA & FOIA Improvement Act) and 29 USC 794d (Rehab Act § 508).


As for your search and claim of no records, I believe you likely searched the "FOIA inbox" account foia@sss.gov. My request was about the chief FOIA officer's emails, i.e. the primary official @sss.gov email used by Craig T. Brown, "regardless of subject matter" — not about FOIA request emails, e.g. not about emails to or from foia@sss.gov. I therefore believe you did not search or provide the records identified, and appeal items 1-3 on that basis.

Sincerely,
Sai

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Delaware Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Underground storage tank (UST) and leaking UST (LUST) information for Cartanza Grain Inc. located at 102 Columbus Drive in Dover (facility ID 10152639). Please include the following record types, if available: UST registration/notification forms; UST inspection reports; UST closure documentation; the initial LUST incident report(s); the initial LUST site investigation; quarterly groundwater monitoring reports; remedial action plan(s); remedial action completion report(s); and LUST incident closure/No Further Action (NFA) documentation. Project no. K9407154.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jonathan Rudenberg, a citizen of Delaware, in coordination with Caitlin Downey.

communications.subject: Minnesota Government Data Practices Act Request: GDPA Request: Fusus logs
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Minnesota Government Data Practices Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) User manuals, handbooks, or comparable instructional documents provided to the department by Fusus regarding any Fusus product the agency uses.

2) User manuals, handbooks, policies, protocols, or comparable instructional documents developed by the department pertaining to the use of any Fusus product.

3) Audit logs/audit trails documenting each time a department account has accessed live or recorded video footage through the Fusus platforms from 1/1/2024 until the date this request is processed.

4) Metadata for each Intelligent AI Alert generated by the department's Fusus system from 1/1/2024 until the date this request is processed. Fusus Intelligent AI Alerts automatically notify authorized users when Fusus AI-connected cameras detect pre-defined events (e.g. a fight) or profiles (e.g. a vehicle of interest). Please note that I am not requesting the video footage or any personally identifying information associated with the alert, but rather the metadata. Metadata may include, but is not limited to: the type of alert, the date and time of the alert, who received the alert, locations associated with the alert, and algorithmic confidence scores associated with the alert. This metadata should be stored in a database and so I ask that you provide it to me as a .csv, .xls, or other database filetype.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

e

Data Requested: First and Last namee 
To Whom It May Concern: Pursuant to the Minnesota Government Data Practices Act, I hereby request the following records: 
Describe other data: 1) User manuals, handbooks, or comparable instructional documents provided to the department by Fusus regarding any Fusus product the agency uses. 2) User manuals, handbooks, policies, protocols, or comparable instructional documents developed by the department pertaining to the use of any Fusus product. 3) Audit logs/audit trails documenting each time a department account has accessed live or recorded video footage through the Fusus platforms from 1/1/2024 until the date this request is processed. 4) Metadata for each Intelligent AI Alert generated by the department's Fusus system from 1/1/2024 until the date this request is processed. Fusus Intelligent AI Alerts automatically notify authorized users when Fusus AI-connected cameras detect pre-defined events (e.g. a fight) or profiles (e.g. a vehicle of interest). Please note that I am not requesting the video footage or any personally identifying information associated with the alert, but rather the metadata. Metadata may include, but is not limited to: the type of alert, the date and time of the alert, who received the alert, locations associated with the alert, and algorithmic confidence scores associated with the alert. This metadata should be stored in a database and so I ask that you provide it to me as a .csv, .xls, or other database filetype. The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. Jeremy Barr

communications.subject: Request for More Time
communications.communication:
December 21, 2018 
Jeremy Barr MuckRock News 
DEPT MR 64300 
411A Highland Ave. 
Somerville, MA 02144 

Re: Freedom of Information Act Request NGC19-102 
Dear Mr. Barr: 
You submitted a Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to our office on November 27, 2018 via FOIAonline. We assigned your request the above internal tracking number in addition to your FOIAOnline tracking number NARA-NGC-2019-000134. In your request, you asked for: All email communications pertaining to the Saturday, November 24 wedding of MSNBC anchors Joe Scarborough and Mika Brzezinski at the National Archives. Please include emails containing references to "Scarborough," "Brzezinski," "Morning Joe," and "MSNBC" sent during the last six months. I am also requesting any official internal documents pertaining to the planning and coordination of the wedding. 
Your request falls within the “unusual circumstances” categories contemplated by the FOIA, 5 U.S.C. §552 (a) (6) (B) (iii) (I) (II) and (III), and we need additional time to respond to your request beyond the twenty business days provided by the FOIA statute. We had to reach out to several offices to search for and collect any responsive records, and we need additional time to finish the search and review any search results. In addition, we may have to consult with other offices of the agency that have a substantial interest in the subject matter. 
To enable us to respond more quickly to you, you do have the option to reformulate your request to reduce the amount of time required to complete our search and review, or to arrange an alternative time frame for the processing of this request. 
We regret the necessity of this delay, but assure you that we will process your request as soon as possible. If you have any questions you may contact me. You may also contact our FOIA Public Liaison, Gary M. Stern for assistance at 8601 Adelphi Road, College Park, MD 20740-6002, 301-837-1750, Garym.Stern@nara.gov. 
Sincerely, 
Susan Gillett Government Information Specialist 
Office of General Counsel 
Tel: 301-837-3409 
Email: susan.gillett@nara.gov

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Agency Roster (Sacramento County Sheriff's Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Please provide records sufficient to show a current staff roster of all sworn employees with your agency.

Please include;
- first and last name of each employee with their corresponding;
- badge number
- employee identification number
- hire date
- rank or position
- assigned duty station/substation/precinct/location
- current salary

This request applies to ALL sworn Department employees, including those at substations.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Marcus Boyd

title: Request to DEA for production assistance agreements between 2017 and 2023

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Request to DEA for production assistance agreements between 2017 and 2023
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any production assistance agreements signed by the Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) with any film or television productions, inclusive of the years 2017-2023.

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation. These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. Attached is a document with organization letterhead confirming my position, as well as the organization's 501(c)(3) application and approval form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

communications.subject: DEA FOIA/PA Case Number: 24-00589-F
communications.communication:
Dear Brett Carollo: This e-mail responds to your Freedom of Information Act/Privacy Act (FOIA/PA) request dated March 7, 2024, received by the Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA), FOIA/PA Unit, seeking access to DEA records.  Your request has been opened and assigned the following case number: 24-00589-F.  Please include this case number when communicating with this office. The records you seek require searches in another office or offices, and so your request falls within "unusual circumstances."  See 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B)(i)-(iii).  Because of these unusual circumstances, we are extending the time limit to respond to your request beyond the ten additional days provided by the statute.  We have not yet completed a search to determine whether there are records within the scope of your request.  The time needed to process your request will necessarily depend on the complexity of our records search and on the volume and complexity of any records located.  For your information, this office assigns incoming requests to one of three tracks:  simple, complex, or expedited.  Each request is then handled on a first-in, first-out basis in relation to other requests in the same track.  Simple requests usually receive a response in approximately one month, whereas complex requests take longer than a month to complete.  At this time, your request has been assigned to the complex track.  You may wish to narrow the scope of your request to limit the number of potentially responsive records or agree to an alternative time frame for processing, should records be located; or you may wish to await the completion of our records search to discuss either of these options. We regret the necessity of this delay, but please be assured that your request will be processed as soon as possible.  If you have any questions or wish to discuss reformulation or an alternative time frame for the processing of your request, you may contact our FOIA Requester Service Center at (571) 776-2300, or e-mail your correspondence to DEA.FOIA@dea.gov. In addition, you may wish to visit our website at www.dea.gov to determine if the information you are requesting is already available to the public.  You may contact our FOIA Public Liaison at (571) 776-2300 for any further assistance and to discuss any aspect of your request.  Additionally, you may contact the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) at the National Archives and Records Administration to inquire about the FOIA mediation services they offer.  The contact information for OGIS is as follows: Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, Room 2510, 8601 Adelphi Road, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001; e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at (202) 741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448; or facsimile at (202) 741-5769. Sincerely, 
FOIA/PA Unit FOIA & Information Law Section Office of Chief Counsel Drug Enforcement Administration 
PRIVACY ACT NOTICE:  This e-mail (including any attachments herein) may contain personal and privileged information that requires protection in compliance with the Privacy Act of 1974 (5 U.S.C. § 552a).  Any use of this information by anyone other than the intended recipient is prohibited.  If you have received this communication in error, please immediately delete all copies of this information and notify me by e-mail.  The use, dissemination, distribution, or reproduction of this communication by unintended recipients is not authorized and may be unlawful.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #24-00589-F
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern,

This message pertains to FOIA request #24-00589-F. I wish to appeal the finding that the requested records are exempt from FOIA release. It does not seem reasonable that general information about official DEA collaborations with feature films or TV shows would meet the exemption requirements. 

If the appeal is rejected, I request (in order to help inform future FOIA requests with DEA) to know if DEA considers any and all information pertaining to collaborations between DEA and the entertainment industry exempt from FOIA.

Thank you.

Brett Carollo

title: Public Records Request on water quality reports

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Public Records Request on water quality reports
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, the Florida Public Records Law, Chapter 119, and the Freedom of Information Act I hereby request the following records:

1. Water Quality Reports: Source of the water, levels of contaminants, etc.
2. Water Testing Results: Results for pollutants or contaminants in the water such as high levels of nutrients, bacteria, and algae. 
3. Studies and reports on algae bloom mitigation efforts: What has been done to address this kind of issue in the past and how effective each measure was. 


The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Erica Forster
eforster@tulane.edu

Subject: DEP Public Records Request 00161928 - 5004w00002rIkW4 [ ref:!00DG00i115.!5004w02rIkW4:ref ]


Thank you for contacting the Florida Department of Environmental Protection with your public records request.  Your request has been logged into our system and assigned case number 00161928.


Your request will be (or has been) assigned to subject matter experts who will research the requested records and make their findings available to you as soon as this process is complete.  One of our staff will be in touch with you soon to advise you of the status or completion of your request.


Should you have any questions feel free to contact the our central Office of Public Services.  Contact information is provided at the bottom of this email.


Notice of Fees and Charges:  Although many public records are provided at no cost there may be charges for extensive use of staff time and resources (119.07(04) F.S.). Extensive use is defined as more than 30 minutes of staff time. There may also be charges for paper copies, CD/DVDs, postage, technological resources and other expenses.  When possible we will provide you with an estimate of any costs in advance.  Note that when charges are accrued records may not be released until payment has been made in full.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FDA processing
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Greetings.  I request records from your FOIA office staff referencing the need for or implementation of additional hiring or other resources following the production orders in Pub. Health & Med. Professionals for Transparency v. FDA, Civ. A. No. 21-1058 (N.D. Tex.) and/or Pub. Health & Med. Professionals for Transparency v. FDA, Civ. A. No. 22-915 (N.D. Tex.).  This includes without limitation documents referencing the amount of additional resources needed to comply with those orders without increasing overall backlogs and how the amount of actual resources compares to the amount expected to be needed.

I also request records from your FOIA office staff dated in the last two years referencing the amount of resourcing needed to reduce FDA's backlog and any effort to obtain that resourcing.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Matthew Topic

communications.subject: Welcome to the Public Disclosure System!
communications.communication:
Rose Terse, 
 
Thank you for registering with King County Prosecuting Attorney Public Disclosure System. If you have never used this system, your account has been created by a staff person at King County. 
 
Once your email address has been verified, you can log in to the system to update any contact or password information and to track the progress of your request. 
 
 Login: 179003-27442182@requests.muckrock.com 
 
To verify your email address, the following activation link to set a password will be active for 24 hours.

communications.subject: Public Disclosure Request :: P018038-010625
communications.communication:
Dear Rose Terse: 
Thank you for your interest in public records of King County Prosecuting Attorney. Your request has been received and is being processed in accordance with the State of Washington Public Records Act, Chapter 42.56 RCW. Your request was received in this system on 1/6/2025 and given the reference number P018038-010625 for tracking purposes. Our regular business hours are Monday through Friday, 8:30 AM to 4:30 PM Pacific Time. If your request is submitted outside our regular business hours then your request will be received in our office the next business day. Records Requested: To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All current "Brady lists" and "Giglio lists" (per Brady v. Maryland/Giglio v. United States) maintained by your office.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

Upload documents directly: https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Fking-county-prosecuting-attorney-17650%252Fbrady-list-january-2025-king-county-prosecuting-attorney-179003%252F%253Femail%253Dkingcountyprosecutor%252540govqa.us&url_auth_token=AABbgy5ZyfrmdgCNqBAVCw7S0vc%3A1tUzQf%3Aym6_rji_0HG3n4ts6S9F0rvNcr17N64W-AyidTqjxoQ 
Not all public documents are available in electronic format. If the document(s) requested are not available electronically, we will make them available for inspection or by paper copy in accordance with the Public Records Act, Chapter 42.56 RCW. 
 
Your request will be forwarded to the relevant division(s) to locate the information you seek and to determine the volume and any costs associated with satisfying your request. You will be contacted about the availability and/or provided with copies of the records in question. 
 
PLEASE NOTE: The State of Washington Public Records Act, Chapter 42.56 RCW, does not require a governmental body to create new information, to do legal research, or to answer questions. 
 
You can monitor the progress of your request at the link below and you'll receive an email when your request has been completed. Again, thank you for using the Public Disclosure System. 
King County Prosecuting Attorney

communications.subject: New Message :: R000338-073024
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 

RE: FOIL Records Request of July 30, 2024, Reference # R000338-073024 
Dear Riford, 
The NYS Department of Financial Services received a FOIL request from you on July 30, 2024. You requested: "Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records: 
1.) 2024 or most recent roster of any and all New York State Department of Financial Services employees located at the Buffalo, NY HQ. Please include the first name, last name, date of hire, yearly or hourly pay rate, position, and department. 
The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 
In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 
Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires." 
The New York State Department of Financial Services (DFS) is still in the process of reviewing the records that you requested, and thus requires additional time to respond to your request. 
DFS will endeavor to provide you the determination of your FOIL request by February 06, 2025, or sooner if possible. However, if DFS is unable to complete its review by that time, you will then be provided an update on the progress of your FOIL request. Your continued patience is greatly appreciated. 
Sincerely, 
Idel Lendoff 
Executive Assistant 
NYS Department of Financial Services

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request #R000338-073024
communications.communication:
Dear NYS DFS Appeals,

I am appealing the constructive denial of my FOIL request submitted on 07/29/2024. NYS Dept. of Financial Services has had ample time to provide the records and has not and has repeatedly extended the timeframe for which records are to be provided. As such, I am consider this a constructive denial of records as define by the NYS FOIL. Thank you.

title: Open Records Request: Community Public Safety Grants

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Open Records Request: Community Public Safety Grants
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

According to a press release from Gov. Kemp's office on June 8, 2023, the Governor's office awarded more than $83.5 million in grants for 118 qualified projects as part of the Community Public Safety Grant program. This included a total of four grants to the Doraville Police Department described in additional documents provided by the Governor: https://gov.georgia.gov/press-releases/2023-06-08/gov-kemp-announces-835m-community-public-safety-grant-awards#:~:text=In%20accordance%20with%20grant%20requirements,violence%20resulting%20from%20the%20pandemic.

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of all documents, including but not limited to, applications, agreements, and reporting documents from the "Community Public Safety Grant" program for the grant received by the Catoosa County Sheriff's Office as described in the Governor's press release and additional documents.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

e

communications.subject: New Jersey Open Public Records Act Request: NJ Drones
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Jersey Open Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All records related to aerial sightings reported in New Jersey during November and December 2024. These sightings, widely described as “mystery drones” or Unidentified Aerial Phenomena (UAP), have been the subject of significant public interest and media coverage.

This request specifically seeks access to all records created, received, or modified between November 1, 2024, and the date of this request's fulfillment. To ensure the identification of all responsive materials, this request includes references to "mystery drones," "UAP," "unidentified flying objects (UFOs)," "unmanned aerial systems (UAS)," "unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs)," "aerial anomalies," or any similar terminology used to describe these aerial sightings.

The requested records include, but are not limited to:

Audio and Video Files: All audio or video files received, recorded, or obtained by the department related to these sightings. This includes recordings made by departmental surveillance equipment, body-worn cameras, dashboard cameras, or agency-operated drones, as well as media submitted by citizens, contractors, or third parties. I request the original or highest-resolution versions of these files and associated metadata, including timestamps, geolocation data, technical specifications of recording devices, and any embedded identifiers for classification, dissemination tracking, or chain of custody.

Associated Analyses and Documentation: All investigative reports, intelligence summaries, or briefings prepared in connection with these sightings. This includes assessments of their origin, behavior, or potential significance, such as whether they posed a security, safety, or privacy threat. I also request documentation of decisions or deliberations regarding the classification, distribution, or public disclosure of information related to these events.

Communications and Directives: All internal and inter-agency communications referencing these aerial phenomena, including any correspondence that references "mystery drones," UAP, or similar terms. This includes records of communications with external entities, such as contractors, private organizations, foreign governments or international bodies, and federal, state, or local agencies involved in investigating or responding to these incidents.

Records of Federal Collaboration: All records documenting referrals, consultations, or information sharing with federal agencies such as the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA), Department of Defense (DoD), Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), or any other relevant entities.

If the scope of this request is deemed overly broad, I am willing to work with your office to refine it to ensure the timely identification and release of responsive records. I also request that responsive records be provided in their original electronic format, preserving all metadata.

If any portions of the requested records are exempt under public records laws, I request that non-exempt portions be released. For any classified materials, I request a mandatory declassification review under applicable laws, including Executive Order 13526.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Bill Gagnon

communications.subject: Notice of Special Service Charge to Gagnon, Bill  Date: January 2, 2025
communications.communication:
Mr. Bill Gagnon,

You have filed an OPRA request for audio recordings related to the reporting of mystery drones, UAVs, UAPs, UAS, UFOs and "aerial anomalies. Calls placed to this Agency between November 1, 2024 and December 28, 2024 number about 100 calls. Due to the number of calls and the time required to review and redact "Personal Identifying Information (PII)" from these calls Special Service Charge will be applied. Please see the attached documents which explain the Special Service Charge.

If you wish to continue with this request then you must respond in writing within 7 days of this email. Failure to do so, will render this request closed. Payment must be made via check to the COUNTY OF OCEAN C/O Michael Zolezi Ocean County Sheriff's Office, Records Custodian. The check must clear before this agency begins to process your OPRA request. Any questions or concerns please contact me at MZolezi@co.ocean.nj.us<mailto:MZolezi@co.ocean.nj.us>.

Best Regards,

Michael Zolezi
Records Custodian
Ocean County Sheriff's Office

MZolezi@co.ocean.nj.us<mailto:MZolezi@co.ocean.nj.us>

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Police Staff Roster (October 2024)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Staff roster including but not limited to first and last names, job titles, areas of assignment, and badge, serial, and other identifying numbers. In order of preference, I would prefer that this data be provided as: plain text with comma-separated-values (i.e., a "CSV" file), OpenDocument spreadsheet, Excel spreadsheet, or the native electronic format of the software from which this information is retrieved in fulfillment of my request. I specifically request that you not create a new record for me by rendering to PDF or by printing your electronic record then scanning it to make a series of images of the printed data.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: CBP records, Harry Belafonte
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any and all DHS/CBP records regarding Harry Belafonte (birth name "Harold George Bellanfanti Jr."), a singer, activist, and actor with date of birth March 1, 1927.  

Belafonte is widely reported to have died in April 2023  (see article in PDF, by Italie  Hillel. “Harry Belafonte, Activist and Entertainer, Dies at 96.” Associated Press, 25 Apr. 2023, apnews.com/article/harry-belafonte-dead-2d8cbdf0043e4383a6c4a85c862cdbe1. Accessed 25 Apr. 2023.). Records concerning Belafonte as a subject should thus be assumed free from FOIA Exemption 6, 7(C) and the Privacy Act. 

In particular I request any record of Belafonte in relation to an investigation or ongoing surveillance, as well as any records of personal travel including (not exclusively) any crossing of a border or referral for secondary screening. 

Please conduct a search of all systems of records for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, agencies and companies. Particular systems of records of interest include (not exclusively):

• DHS/ALL-041	External Biometric Records (EBR)
• DHS/CBP-001	Import Information System (IIS)
• DHS/CBP-002	Global Enrollment System (GES)
• DHS/CBP-003	Credit/Debit Card Data System
• DHS/CBP-005	Advance Passenger Information System (APIS)
• DHS/CBP-006	Automated Targeting System (ATS)
• DHS/CBP-007	Border Crossing Information (BCI)
• DHS/CBP-008	Non-Federal Entity Data Systems (NEDS)
• DHS/CBP-009	Electronic System for Travel Authorization (ESTA)
• DHS/CBP-010	Persons Engaged in International Trade in Customs and Border Protection Licensed/Regulated Activities
• DHS/CBP-011	U.S. Customs and Border Protection TECS
• DHS/CBP-012	Closed Circuit Television System 
• DHS/CBP-013	Seized Assets and Case Tracking System (SEACATS)
• DHS/CBP-016	Nonimmigrant Information System (NIIS)
• DHS/CBP-017	Analytical Framework for Intelligence (AFI)
• DHS/CBP-019	Air and Marine Operations Surveillance System (AMOSS)
• DHS/CBP-021	Arrival and Departure Information System (ADIS) 
• DHS/CBP-023	Border Patrol Enforcement Records (BPER)
• DHS/CBP-024	Intelligence Records System (CIRS)
• DHS/USCIS/ICE/CBP-001	Alien File, Index, and National File Tracking System of Records.

If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that CBP has no other copies of said records.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

T. McElwee

communications.subject: CBP FOIA - CBP-FO-2023-076128
communications.communication:
T. McElweeN/AMuckRock News, DEPT MR144978263 Huntington AveBoston, Massachusetts 0211504/28/2023CBP-FO-2023-076128Dear T. McElwee: This notice acknowledges receipt of your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP) received on 4/27/2023.  Please use the following unique FOIA tracking number CBP-FO-2023-076128 to track the status of your request.  If you have not already done so, you must create a SecureRelease account. This is the only method available to check the status of your pending FOIA request.Provisions of the Act allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS FOIA regulations outlined on the DHS website, https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2016/11/22/2016-28095/freedom-of-information-act-regulations. By submitting your request, you have agreed to pay up to $25.00 in applicable processing fees, if any fees associated with your request exceed this amount, CBP shall contact you.  Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request.  Consistent with 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, CBP processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt.  Although CBP’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period in certain circumstances pursuant to 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(c).  CBP’s FOIA Division is working hard to reduce the amount of time necessary to respond to FOIA requests.  We truly appreciate your continued patience.  For additional information please consult CBP FOIA website please click on FOIA Act Resources or visit http://www.cbp.gov/site-policy-notices/foia. Sincerely,U.S. Customs and Border Protection 
This message (including any attachments) contains confidential information intended for a specific individual and purpose, and is protected by law. If you are not the intended recipient, you should delete this message and any disclosure, copying, or distribution
 of this message, or the taking of any action based on it, by you is strictly prohibited. 
Deloitte refers to a Deloitte member firm, one of its related entities, or Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu Limited ("DTTL"). Each Deloitte member firm is a separate legal entity and a member of DTTL. DTTL does not provide services to clients. Please see www.deloitte.com/about
 to learn more.

communications.communication:
T. McElwee 
N/A 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR144978 
263 Huntington Ave 
Boston, Massachusetts 02115 

01/14/2025 

CBP-FO-2023-076128 

Dear T. McElwee: 

This is a final response to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP) for entry-exit and/or I-94 records. 

CBP is granting your request under the FOIA, Title 5 U.S.C. § 552.  After carefully reviewing the responsive documents, CBP has determined that they are approved for release in their entirety, no deletions or exemptions have been applied. 

For your information, Congress excluded three discrete categories of law enforcement and national security records from the requirements of the FOIA. See 5 U.S.C. 552(c).  This response is limited to those records that are subject to the requirements of the FOIA. This is a standard notification that is given to all our requesters and should not be taken as an indication that excluded records do, or do not, exist. 

You may contact CBP's FOIA Public Liaison, Charlyse Hoskins, by sending an email via your SecureRelease account, mailing a letter to 1300 Pennsylvania Avenue, NW MS 1181, Washington DC, 20229 or by calling 202-325-0150. (If you need telecommunication relay service (TRS) assistance to communicate with the CBP FOIA Office and you are in the United States, please dial 711 to obtain TRS assistance and notify the Communications Assistant that you want to contact the CBP FOIA Office at the telephone number (202) 325-0150). The FOIA Public Liaison is able to assist in advising on the requirements for submitting a request, assist with narrowing the scope of a request, assist in reducing delays by advising the requester on the type of records to request, suggesting agency offices that may have responsive records and receive questions or concerns about the agency’s FOIA process. Please notate file number CBP-FO-2023-076128 on any future correspondence to CBP related to this request. 

Please note that this message has been sent from an unmonitored e-mail account. Any messages sent to this account will not be read. 

Sincerely, 
U.S. Customs and Border Protection

This request concerns Inspection 1709320.015 and Report ID 0214700 concerning Fire Island Marine Services LLC at location 99 Maple Avenue Bay Shore, New York. 11706, which investigation was opened Nov. 8th 2023.  Request is made for the following documents,
1. All citations or penalties issued to the Employer,  Fire Island Marine Services LLC as a result of the investigation and final disposition including appeals and including amounts paid.

5. All witness statements or memoranda, interviews conducted as part of the investigation. whether reduced to writing or recorded.
6. All communications from the Employer Fire Island Marine Services concerning Abatement or documentation of abatement.

Tabak Mellusi & Shisha

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Amanda Milius
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Dear FOIA Officer,

Under the Freedom of Information Act (5 U.S.C. 552), I request access to and copies of all records, including but not limited to electronic records, emails, correspondence, meeting notes, and other communications involving Mike Cernovich, Jack Posobiec, and any career or political officials within the Department of State during the administration of President Donald Trump (January 20, 2017, to January 20, 2021).

Please include all relevant documents that detail communications, meetings, and correspondences with these individuals, as well as any notes, agendas, or mentions of them in communications with Department of State officials. I am interested in understanding the nature and extent of their interactions with the Department of State during this period.

I understand that there may be fees for this request and would appreciate it if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. Please notify me prior to your incurring any expenses in excess of $1000.

If my request is denied in whole or part, I ask that you justify all deletions by reference to specific exemptions of the act. I will also expect you to release all segregable portions of otherwise exempt material. I reserve the right to appeal your decision to withhold any information or to deny a waiver of fees.

As I am making this request in the public interest, for the purpose of disseminating information regarding the public activities and operations of the U.S. Department of State to the general public, I request that you waive any fees associated with the processing of this request.

Please respond to this request within 20 business days, as outlined by the statute. Thank you for your consideration of this request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Trevor Davis

communications.communication:
*THIS EMAIL BOX IS NOT MONITORED, PLEASE DO NOT REPLY TO THIS EMAIL.** Dear Mr.Davis: This email acknowledges receipt of your April 25, 2024, Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) (5 U.S.C. § 552) request received by the U.S. Department of State, Office ofInformation Programs and Services on April 25, 2024.  request for access to and copies of all records, including but not limited to electronic records, emails, correspondence, meeting notes, and other communications involving Mike Cernovich, Jack Posobiec, and any career or political officials within the Department of State during the administration of President Donald Trump (January 20, 2017, to January 20, 2021)(Date Range for Record Search: From 1/20/2017 To 1/20/2021). 

You are seeking a copy of  Unless you advise otherwise, we will treat as non-responsive anycompilations of publicly available news reports and any publicly availabledocuments not created by the U.S. government, such as mass-distribution emailsfrom news media.  This Office assigned your request the subjectreference number and placed it in the complex processing track where it will beprocessed as quickly as possible.  See 22 CFR § 171.11(h). 
This Office will not be able to respond within the 20 daysprovided by the statute due to “unusual circumstances.”  See 5 U.S.C.§ 552(a)(6)(B)(i)-(iii).  In this instance, the unusual circumstancesinclude the need to search for and collect requested records from otherDepartment offices or Foreign Service posts. 
If you have any questionsregarding your request, would like to narrow the scope or arrange analternative time frame to speed its processing, or would like an estimated dateof completion, please contact our FOIA Requester Service Center or our FOIA PublicLiaison by email at ortelephone at 202-261-8484.  Additionally, you may contact the Office ofGovernment Information Services (OGIS) at the National Archives and RecordsAdministration to inquire about the FOIA mediation services they offer. The contact information for OGIS is as follows: Office of GovernmentInformation Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, email at (mailto:FOIAstatus@state.gov) FOIAstatus@state.gov ; telephone at202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448; or facsimile at 202-741-5769. communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: HART contracts
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Contracts, policy agreements, memoranda of understanding, and all other contractual agreements between the Department of Homeland Security and the Northrop Grumman Corporation pertaining to the development and implementation of the Homeland Advanced Recognition Technology System (HART), including, but no limited to all contractual materials associated with delivery order HSHQDC14DE2035-HSHQDC17J00370.

If any redactions, deletions, or withholdings are made, please include explanations thereof.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Felipe De La Hoz

communications.subject: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: VMI Speakers
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All records from April 2024 to the date of this request of communications, coordination, contracts, quotes, proposals, purchase orders, agreements or other arrangements for cadets, staff, and faculty training, workshops, presentations, instruction and/or other offerings from any outside person, organization and/or contractor that are or will be applicable for services provided during the 2024 – 2025 academic year. Scope is regardless if the services were provided or not. These records are between any member of the VMI Faculty or staff including, without limitation, the VMI Procurement Office, Superintendent’s Office, Human Resources Office, Inspector General/Title IX office, Diversity, Equity and Inclusion Office and/or any others involved in the identification, selection, coordination, acquisition and delivery of trainings, workshop(s), presentations and/or instruction regardless if they are purchased and/or provided at no cost. This includes and/or any coordination and/or procurements and/or sessions completed or ongoing regardless if agreements were reached or not and/or if training, workshops, presentations, instruction and/or other offerings were provided, not provided or are planned. The scope of this request includes, without limitation any and all speaker bios and proposed or provided presentations, trainings, workshop structures, topics and/or programs of instruction. A the minimum these should include, without limitation, BigSpeak Inc.,Campus Outreach Services Inc.,Kara Dixon Vuic,Raven Solomon Enterprises LLC,Rainbow Bridge,NewPoint Strategies,Modern Military Association,Passageways, Inc.,Visions,Woods Rogers PLC. For the purpose of this FOIA “Records” are defined as any public record subject to disclosure under the Va. FOIA including any writing or recording, paper record, electronic file, audio, video recording, or any other format. This term shall mean all relevant data and information in the Custodian’s possession defined in [a] Requester’s General Subject of Inquiry and [b] Specific Subjects of Inquiry including but not limited to letters, notes, drafts, legal instruments, proposals, marketing materials from vendors, contracts, telephone transcripts, email correspondence, drawings and tables. Includes, without limitation, any and all forms of memorialized information, whether written, graphic, computerized, or stored electronically or on tape.  This definition specifically includes, but is not limited to, drafts, originals, copies, handwritten notes or comments, letters, correspondence, e-mails, records of discussions, memoranda, telegrams, telephone logs and records, teletypes, appointment books, meeting agenda or minutes, reports, briefings, presentations, studies, analyses, communications with government bodies, interoffice and intra-office communications with any party whatsoever, computer programs and printouts, social media communications, including, but not limited, to FaceTime, Instagram, FaceBook.com, text messages, and other records or voice records, films or tapes As well as any screenshots or other record showing calls of which there are no other records were made.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tom Nash, a citizen of Virginia, in coordination with Anonymous.

communications.subject: [External Message Added] Virginia Military Institute public records request #24-92
communications.communication:
Virginia Military Institute ************************************************************************ A message was sent to you regarding record request #24-92: After consultation with the individuals responsible for the information you requested, I have determined that the estimated cost of fulfilling your request is $578.16. As you may be aware, § 2.2-3704. F. of the Code of Virginia allows public bodies to charge for accessing, duplicating, supplying, redacting or searching for the requested records. This estimate reflects the following: * Procurement Assistant Director: 1.5 hrs @$66.23 per hour * Procurement Assistant: 8 hrs @ $26.52 per hour * FOIA Assistant: 2 hrs @ $23.34 per hour * Financial Services Specialist: 4 hrs @ $23.86 per hour * Adams Center Administrative Assistant: 2 hrs @ $24.40 * Modern Languages and Cultures Admin. Asst.: 0.5 hrs @ $19.09 per hour * FOIA Officer: 1.5 hrs @ $66.20 per hour Please let us know if you agree to the estimated cost. If you do, we will send you an invoice and, once we receive payment, will begin to process your request. ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at Virginia Military Institute.
Technical support: See our help page

communications.subject: RE: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request #24-92
communications.communication:
Please provide your justification why this request teakes 2 hours of tiem from a FOIA assistant AND 1.5 hours from the FOIA officer him/herself (total of 3.5 hours) just to send out the request for the records, receive the responses, do a review of what should be routine files kept as part of doing business, and simply uploading them to the system? What specific tasks are being performed that result in what appears to be an excessive workload estimate?

Also, when contracts are automated in the eVA system and should be on the VMI Procurment website, why is there a requirement for 1.5 hours of a Procurment assistant director AND 8 hours (one full day) fir a procurment assistant? What specific tasks are each performing?

While I await your responses and justification to the questions above, I would like to initially scope my request to the following that should reduce or eliminate any costs.

Initiall scope the records to  the period May 2024 to the date of this response for: Raven Solomon Enterprises LLC,Rainbow Bridge,NewPoint Strategies,Modern Military Association.

communications.subject: [External Message Added] Virginia Military Institute public records request #24-92
communications.communication:
Virginia Military Institute ************************************************************************ A message was sent to you regarding record request #24-92: In addition to procurement records, your initial request asked for records related to "... communications, coordination..." of "... cadets, staff, and faculty training, workshops, presentations, instruction... " While contracts and other procurement records would be publicly available on the eVA website, the communications and coordination records would not. Since tracking down these records includes many offices around post, this is what constitutes the time of the FOIA assistant. The time for the procurement staff constitutes their estimate for searching for identifying contracts related to "training, workshops, presentations, instruction" and to search for communication and coordination of said contracts. The FOIA officer reviews all records prior to their release to the public. Per your instruction, your request will be revised to include records related to Raven Solomon Enterprises LLC, Rainbow Bridge, NewPoint Strategies, and Modern Military Association between May 1, 2024, and January 5, 2025. A new estimate will be provided if the subject matter experts determine the request will cost more than $50. ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at Virginia Military Institute.
Technical support: See our help page

communications.subject: RE: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request #24-92
communications.communication: Thank you.

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: ESD fund applications and agreements with WEDI
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

The formal applications and final funding agreements for two payments to Westminster Economic Development Initiative by Empire State Development programs.

1. $539,187 through WNY Regional Economic Development Council

2. $500,000 through Better Buffalo Fund, through NYS Homes and Community Renewal

Also, any correspondence related to the application, funding agreement, or related matters.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew

communications.subject: [Records Center] FOIL Records Request :: R000223-091124
communications.communication:
RE: FOIL Records Request of September 11, 2024, Reference # R000223-091124 Dear Andrew Andrew, New York State Empire State Development received a public records request from you on September 11, 2024. Your request seeks: Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records: 

The formal applications and final funding agreements for two payments to Westminster Economic Development Initiative by Empire State Development programs. 

1. $539,187 through WNY Regional Economic Development Council 
2. $500,000 through Better Buffalo Fund, through NYS Homes and Community Renewal 
Also, any correspondence related to the application, funding agreement, or related matters. 
New York State Empire State Development has reviewed its files and has located responsive records to your request. Please log in to the FOIL Records Access Center at the following link to retrieve the responsive records. FOIL Records Request - R000223-091124 Pursuant to Public Officers Law §87(2)(b), ESD has redacted information and documents that “if disclosed would constitute an unwarranted invasion of personal privacy under the provisions of subdivision two of section eighty-nine of this article.” 
Public Officers Law §87(2)(i), ESD has withheld certain records as they contain information that “if disclosed, would jeopardize the capacity of an agency or an entity that has shared information with an agency to guarantee the security of its information technology assets, such assets encompassing both electronic information systems and infrastructures.” Pursuant to Public Officers Law §89(4)(a), you have thirty (30) days to appeal this determination. An appeal of any portion of this determination should be directed to Empire State Development’s appeals officer, New York State Urban Development Corporation d/b/a Empire State Development, 633 Third Avenue, 37th Floor, New York, NY 10017, FOILAppeal@esd.ny.gov. (mailto:FOILAppeal@esd.ny.gov) Sincerely, 

Jaclyn Clemmer 
Senior Counsel, Records Access Officer

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Paris - Climate Accord
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

EFOIA Request

For the FBI in relation to 
New England field offices (all)
Los Angeles Office
Las Vegas Field Office
Florida Field Offices
Texas Field Offices

For records reasonably described to be found within the Washington Offices, and the Inspections/OPR offices, and the Offices of the General Counsel
For years: 2015-2021

Pursuant to the testimony as highlighted by the former FBI General Counsel Dana Boente to the Senate Judiciary :

https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Dana%20Boente%20Redacted%20FINAL.pdf?fbclid=IwAR25E0f_Ue-X5J2WrF8tSkowXzoeRGaMFRzroS-DVmzxcbeKa2be_QhH2ss


on page 22, lines, 3,4,5 and 6, quoting 
"3 climate survey that the FBI does to sort of take the
4 temperature, a pulse check, of the various divisions to see
5 if there's problems with morale and maybe retention issues
6 or whatnot."

Please produce any and all records in your custody related to said types of internal memorandum related to the offices as sought.  Please include any email correspondence in relation to said records. 

If any of said records sought have already been disclosed publicly, you're welcomed to respond to this request with a hyperlink to a Reading Room or Vault location.

Vaughn Index requested

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

William Fernandes

Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 104 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 853 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,786 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,500 days for processing.

communications.subject: Montana Freedom of Information Act Request: Agency Roster (Hamilton Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Montana Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Please provide records sufficient to show a current staff roster of all sworn employees with your agency.

Please include;
- first and last name of each employee with their corresponding;
- badge number
- employee identification number
- hire date
- rank or position
- assigned duty station/substation/precinct/location
- current salary

This request applies to ALL sworn Department employees, including those at substations.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Marcus Boyd
Received your request.  We are compiling the information.  You should receive it by 1/15/2025.
See up-loaded file as per your request.
